[[File:JourneyContinued.jpg|thumb|First UK edition (publ. [[OUP]])]]
'''''Journey Continued: An Autobiography''''' is the second part of [[Alan Paton]]'s autobiography, the first being ''[[Towards the Mountain]]''.
Paton had completed the writing and correction of the volume, but he died before its publication in 1988.<ref>Journey Continued by Alan Paton, Oxford University Press, 1988, {{ISBN|978-0-19-219237-0}}.</ref>
==Topics==
The book addresses a wide variety of topics, personal, professional, philosophical, and political. For example, it discusses the way in which Paton's ''[[Cry, The Beloved Country]]'' was adapted for [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/04/02/books/reflections-on-beloved-country.html|date=1988-04-02|access-date=2016-12-12|last=Battersby|first=John D.|title=Reflections On 'Beloved Country'|publisher=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> but it also discusses the Christian basis for Paton's activism.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-01-14/books/bk-134_1_alan-paton|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=1990-01-14|title=JOURNEY CONTINUED: An Autobiography by Alan Paton|access-date=2016-12-12|first=Charles|last=Solomon}}</ref><ref name=ngwenya />
''Journey Continued'' outlines long Paton's and deep involvement with the [[Liberal Party of South Africa]], and his views on [[liberalism]] and its distinctness from other political philosophies.<ref name=ngwenya>{{cite journal|title=The liberal‐Christian vision in Alan Paton's autobiography|journal=Current Writing: Text and Reception in Southern Africa|doi=10.1080/1013929X.1997.9678021|first=Thengani H|last=Ngwenya|volume=9|date=1997|pages=36–56}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Peace Profile: The African Resistance Movement|first=Travis K.|last=Sharp|pages=455–462|doi=10.1080/10402650500374793|journal=[[Peace Review]]|volume=17|year=2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title= Alan Paton and the Rule of Law |journal=[[African Affairs]]|last=Black|first=Michael|pages=53–72|volume=91|number=362|date=January 1992|jstor=722562}}</ref>
==Quotations==
{{Quote|text="Between communists and liberals ... there is a fundamental incompatibility. ... A liberal cannot accept that the use of any means is justifiable if the end is good; a communist can. A liberal shrinks from the idea of a centrally controlled society, and a centrally controlled economy; a communist does not. The liberal belief in the separation of powers is not acceptable to communists. A liberal believes that a centrally controlled economy kills private initiative and drive, and leads to a drab and dreary existence. A liberal believes in the rule of law, the communist believes in the rule of the party." |author=Alan Paton|source=''Journey Continued''<ref>{{cite book|title=Journey Continued: An Autobiography|last=Paton|first=Alan|isbn=9780192192370|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|page=68|year=1988}}</ref>}}
